\begin_layout Standard
In the Sections above, we have provided various derivations of equations
 of motion for density matrix and of (non-)linear responses of various order
 in the external perturbation by light.
 For this we used the most convenient quantum mechanical object we have
 at hand, namely the (reduced) statistical operator (a.k.a.
 density matrix).
 Density matrix is extremely convenient for derivations like this, because
 it allows us to relatively simply account for our lack of knowledge of
 (or disinterest in) some parts of the system that we investigate.
 In stead of using the total statistical operator 
\begin_inset Formula $W(t)$
\end_inset

, which contains all possible information about the state of the whole system
 we investigate (this system in fact includes also the laboratory and the
 scientists in it etc.), we can 
\emph on
reduce
\emph default
 the information by tracing out all 
\emph on
irrelevant
\emph default
 information.
 We only have to decide which DOF are the irrelevant ones and denote them
 as a 
\emph on
bath
\emph default
 or 
\emph on
environment
\emph default
 (let us use the subscript B for these DOF) over which we perform a trace
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\rho(t)={\rm tr}_{B}\left\{ W(t)\right\} .
\end{equation}

\end_inset

If we are lucky, we can derive some effective equations of motion for 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(t)$
\end_inset

 and (almost) eliminate the environment from our thinking.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The trick with density matrix is that 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(t)$
\end_inset

 alone can be used to evaluate all quantities which do not depend on the
 bath.
 In addition it is possible to formulate fenomenological theory of dissipative
 processes using the reduced density matrix.
 This makes 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(t)$
\end_inset

 a very applealing quantity.
 In some sense it is also possible to claim that the density matrix has
 an simpler interpretation that the 
\emph on
state vector
\emph default
 (i.e.
 the wavefunction), but we will show here that this is an illusion.
\end_layout

