\begin_layout Standard
Interpretation of the state vector 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi\rangle$
\end_inset

 is always a bit difficult to swallow, especially for the beginners in quantum
 mechanics.
 Given a quantum mechanical state 
\begin_inset Formula $|a\rangle$
\end_inset

, the element (or component) 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle a|\psi\rangle$
\end_inset

 of the state vector 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi\rangle$
\end_inset

 represent the probability amplitude that the system is in the state 
\begin_inset Formula $|a\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 That is, one has to square the element to get the probability, i.e.
 to something directly measurable (if a detector for state 
\begin_inset Formula $|a\rangle$
\end_inset

 exists):
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{a}=\left|\langle a|\psi\rangle\right|^{2}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The quantity that we propagate in Schr
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
"{o}
\end_layout

\end_inset

dinger equation does not have a 
\emph on
direct physical meaning
\emph default
, it has to be processes after propagation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The density matrix, on the contrary, is conceived in such a way that its
 diagonal elements represent the probabilities directly.
 That's great, because we propagate something 
\emph on
real
\emph default
 again (both in physical and mathematical sense).
 More over, one can include statistics into the density matrix.
 Evolution of an ensemble can be represented by the density matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(t)$
\end_inset

, but it cannot (easily) be done by wavefunction.
 This seems to be a clear advantage for density matrix over wavefunction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Somewhat problematic is the interpretation of the density matrix off-diabonal
 elements.
 While element 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{aa}(t)=\langle a|\rho(t)|a\rangle$
\end_inset

 gives the probability that the system will be measured in state 
\begin_inset Formula $|a\rangle$
\end_inset

, what is given by the element 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{ab}(t)=\langle a|\rho(t)|b\rangle$
\end_inset

? When the density matrix can be represented by a projector on a state vector,
 i.e.
 when
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\rho(t)=|\psi(t)\rangle\langle\psi(t)|,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
c_{a}(t)=\langle a|\psi(t)\rangle,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

is the probability amplitude of the state 
\begin_inset Formula $|a\rangle$
\end_inset

, the off-diagonal element is just a product of two such amplitudes
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\rho_{ab}(t)=c_{a}(t)c_{b}^{*}(t).\label{eq:simple_DM}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The probability amplitudes are back, we did not get rid of them at all.
 A slight advatange of density matrix representation is that it automatically
 cancels the absolute phase, but otherwise we carry the same information
 in the density matrix as we do in wavefunction (not suprisingly).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What about when 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(t)$
\end_inset

 really is the reduced density matrix, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
W(t)=|\Psi(t)\rangle\langle\Psi(t)|,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\rho(t)={\rm tr_{B}\left\{ W(t)\right\} }?
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Now the diagonal elements 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{aa}(t)$
\end_inset

 read as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\rho_{aa}(t)={\rm tr}_{B}\left\{ \langle a|\Psi(t)\rangle\langle\Psi(t)|a\rangle\right\} .
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This element can be given a simple interpretation in all details.
 First, we realize that one can write
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
|\Psi(t)\rangle=\sum_{a}\langle a|\Psi(t)\rangle|a\rangle=\sum_{a}c_{a}(t)\frac{\langle a|\Psi(t)\rangle}{\sqrt{|\langle a|\Psi(t)\rangle|^{2}}}|a\rangle,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
c_{a}(t)=\sqrt{|\langle a|\Psi(t)\rangle|^{2}},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which means that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
|\phi_{a}(t)\rangle=\frac{\langle a|\Psi(t)\rangle}{\sqrt{|\langle a|\Psi(t)\rangle|^{2}}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

is the normalized environmental state vector relative to the state 
\begin_inset Formula $|a\rangle$
\end_inset

 of the reduced system.
 The diagonal element 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{aa}(t)$
\end_inset

 of the total density matrix then reads
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
W_{aa}(t)=\langle a|W(t)|a\rangle=|c_{a}(t)|^{2}|\phi_{a}(t)\rangle\langle\phi_{a}(t)|=\rho_{aa}(t)w_{aa}(t),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{aa}(t)$
\end_inset

 is a density matrix of the bath, relative to the state 
\begin_inset Formula $|a\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 When the system is in state 
\begin_inset Formula $|a\rangle$
\end_inset

, the bath can be assigned a regular normalized density matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{aa}(t)$
\end_inset

.
 This density matrix has the usual interpretation and it describes the state
 of a physical system (in this case the bath).
 By measurement, one can in principle reduce the system to state 
\begin_inset Formula $|a\rangle$
\end_inset

 and then 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{aa}(t)$
\end_inset

 would represent the corresponding state of the bath.
 Only in such a case can one say: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

The bath is in state represented by density matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{aa}(t)$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 In all other cases, the state of the bath is not determined by a single
 density matrix.
 Effectively it is undetermined the same way the state of the subsystem
 itself is undetermined, because teh system and its environment are entangled.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In case of the off-diagonal element 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{ab}(t)$
\end_inset

, there is even more possible confusion about what represents a state of
 what.
 The off-diagonal element of 
\begin_inset Formula $W(t)$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
W_{ab}(t)=\langle a|W(t)|b\rangle=c_{a}(t)c_{b}^{*}(t)|\phi_{a}(t)\rangle\langle\phi_{b}(t)|,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

despite being an operator on the Hilbert space of the environmental DOF,
 is not itself a valid density matrix.
 It can easily have negative diagonal elements, so they cannot represent
 probabilities of finding system in any states.
 This only underlines the fact that a projector 
\begin_inset Formula $|a\rangle\langle b|$
\end_inset

 is not a projector on a state.
 The language used around non-linear response functions, in which 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

system is excited into coherence state
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or so, does not describe any physical states or processes.
 It only describes a formal expressions which one obtains in perturbation
 theory in a language which makes them easier to graps.
 Measurable signals originate from certain elements of the density matrix
 in perturbation theory, but this does not make these elements to represent
 any physical states.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When we trace over 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{ab}(t)$
\end_inset

 we obtain the element 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{ab}(t)$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\rho_{ab}(t)={\rm tr}_{B}\left\{W_{ab}(t)\right\},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

we can see that it is composed of two parts
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\rho_{ab}(t)=c_{a}(t)c_{b}^{*}(t)\langle\phi_{b}(t)|\phi_{a}(t)\rangle,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

one of which looks very much like the simple density matrix of the system
 without interaction with the bath (
\begin_inset Formula $c_{a}(t)c_{b}^{*}(t)$
\end_inset

), see Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:simple_DM"

\end_inset

), and one which corresponds to an overlap between state vectors describing
 the bath relative to the 
\begin_inset Formula $|a\rangle$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $|b\rangle$
\end_inset

 states.
 
\end_layout

